                         Welcome to ABC-PATTERNS   !!!

                                                              ®          TM
   ABC-PATTERNS is a pattern-collection for use with the Amiga  Workbench.

   ABC-PATTERNS requires Workbench 2.0 or higher!

   The patterns are designed for ...
   - a proportional ScreenMode (640x512, for example) with square pixels
   - an 8-color Workbench Screen (3 bitplanes)
   - colors similar to the colors of "MagicWB" (© 1993 by Martin Huttenloher)

   I prefer a more intensive blue (color 3) and red (color 7). You can see
   my Workbench colors by double-clicking @{b}"ABC-Colors"@{ub}. I also included
   @{b}"ABC-Screen"@{ub} (Hires interlaced) to make testing easier.

   @{" How to use " link USAGE}          @{" Contents  " link CONTENTS}          @{" My Request " link REQUEST}
   @{"  Patterns  " link PATTERNS}          @{" Copyright " link COPYRIGHT}          @{" My Address " link ADDRESS}

@endnode
@node USAGE "ABC-Patterns.guide/How to use"

   HOW TO USE:
   ~~~~~~~~~~~
                          For Workbench 3.x ...

   You can copy your favorite ABC-PATTERNS to your Workbench-Disk and select
   them as backgrounds for the Workbench Screen & Windows in the programme
   WBPattern. It is located in the Prefs-Drawer of Workbench 3.x.
   BEFORE you try to load a pattern you should change the colors of your
   Workbench Screen with @{b}ABC-Colors@{ub}! To save the colors permanently use
   "Palette" in the same Drawer.
   THEN you can open WBPattern, choose the location for the pattern (Workbench,
   Windows or Screen) and the type "Picture". Now click on the gadget
   "Select Picture" and select a pattern.

                          For Workbench 2.x ...

   Additional to the above instructions, Workbench 2.x users have to

   - install `NickPrefs` (© by Nicola Salmoria)
   - re-color the patterns with a paint program (like "DPaint") to the
     Workbench-Colors because of the different behaviour of Workbench 2.x.
     Just choose a proportional ScreenMode, import the Workbench-colors,
     load the pattern as a "brush" and re-color it. Then save the brush
     with a new name.

@endnode
@node PATTERNS "ABC-Patterns.guide/Patterns"

   PATTERNS - a short history:
   ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   Version 1.0  (14.07.1994)
   -------------------------
   I created four types of patterns:

   The AmigaAmiga-Patterns consist of two Amiga plates,
   the Checkmark- Patterns consist of checkmarks (the famous Amiga symbol),
   the AmigaCheck-Patterns is a mixture of both and
   the AmigaBig - Patterns is my favourite one, it has a special big format.

   The name "ABC-PATTERNS" is a hint on the filenames of the patterns:

   The A-Series   has a plain background.
   The  B-Series  has a rough background.
   The   C-Series has a wavy  background.

   The number in the filename is the number of the plate-pattern. Some files
   have an additional "B", which corresponds to the brown Amiga letters.
   I hope this helps you in finding your favourite patterns.

   I also included the background patterns Ground.rough and Ground.wavy.

   Version 1.1  (04.10.1994)
   -------------------------
   This is an update to the first release. It contains 111 new patterns:

   The D-Series   has a background with a diagonal matrix.
   The  E-Series  has a background with a vertical matrix.
   The   F-Series has a background with a combined (d & v) matrix.

   Again I included the backgrounds: Ground.D, Ground.E and Ground.F.

@endnode
